# plotting and image tools import seaborn as sns import matplotlib.pyplot as plt from matplotlib.patches import PathPatch from matplotlib.offsetbox import OffsetImage, AnnotationBbox import numpy as np from PIL import Image from matplotlib.collections import PatchCollection from matplotlib.patches import Polygon from transition_image_switches import col_collection, row_collection, diag_collection # shiny express for app interface from shiny import reactive, render from shiny.express import input, render, ui # from plots import bearpieplot # load mathjax to render latex, etc # info from here: https://www.fabriziomusacchio.com/blog/2021-08-10-How_to_use_LaTeX_in_Markdown/ ui.HTML('''''') # assuming that cub is 0-1 years # juvenile is 1-4 years # adult is 4+ years # title ui.page_opts(title="Modeling the Utah Black Bear Population with Eigenvalues and Eigenvectors", fillable=True) # footer = ?? # IMGS = {"matrix" : } # image # ui.setBackgroundImage(src = "image1.jpg") # add sidebar with ui.sidebar(open="closed"): @render.express def valid_warning(): if not check_valid(): ui.markdown("""The inputs you have selected break the model assumptions. Because of this, your results may be invalid.""") ui.markdown("""See the state diagram for additional explanation.""") with ui.tooltip(id="m1_tooltip", placement="right"): ui.input_slider( "m1", "Cub maturation (m1)", min=0, max=100, value=65, step=1, post="%" # pre="", ) ui.HTML("""
""") "The fraction of living cubs in a given year that become living juvenile bears in the next" # https://myfwc.com/wildlifehabitats/wildlife/bear/facts/life-expectancy/ # cub mortality is 25-50% # we'll average 35%, then maturation should be 65% with ui.tooltip(id="s2_tooltip", placement="right"): ui.input_slider( "s2", "Juvenile Stasis (s2)", min=0, max=100, value=50, step=1, post="%" # pre="", ) ui.HTML("""
""") "The fraction of living, juvenile bears in a given year that are still living, juvenile bears in the next" # https://myfwc.com/wildlifehabitats/wildlife/bear/facts/life-expectancy/#:~:text=Two%20of%20the%20biggest%20threats,of%20a%20new%20home%20range. # yearling mortality is 1/4 per year on average similar or greater for older juveniles it seems # adulthood is 'about 4 years old' # we'll assume 0.25 juvenile mortality since this seems more typical for females, and then since juveniles are from 1 year to 4 years, it takes them 3 years to mature, so if it weren't for mortality, about 1/3 or 0.33 would mature every year, or 0.67 don't. So probability of survival is 0.75 and probability of remaining a juvenile is 0.67 so our probability of stasis assuming these are independent is 0.75*0.67\approx 0.5. with ui.tooltip(id="m2_tooltip", placement="right"): ui.input_slider( "m2", "Juvenile maturation (m2)", min=0, max=100, value=25, step=1, post="%" # pre="", ) ui.HTML("""
""") "The fraction of living juvenile bears in a given year that become living adult bears in the next" # https://myfwc.com/wildlifehabitats/wildlife/bear/facts/life-expectancy/#:~:text=Two%20of%20the%20biggest%20threats,of%20a%20new%20home%20range. # yearling mortality is 1/4 per year on average similar or greater for older juveniles it seems # adulthood is 'about 4 years old' # we'll assume 0.25 juvenile mortality since this seems more typical for females, and then since juveniles are from 1 year to 4 years, it takes them 3 years to mature, so if it weren't for mortality, about 1/3 or 0.33 would mature every year, or 0.67 don't. So probability of survival is 0.75 and probability of maturing is 0.33 so our probability of maturation assuming these are independent is 0.75*0.67\approx 0.25. with ui.tooltip(id="s3_tooltip", placement="right"): ui.input_slider( "s3", "Adult Stasis (s3)", min=0, max=100, value=93, step=1, post="%" # pre="", ) ui.HTML("""
""") "The fraction of living, adult bears in a given year that are still living, adult bears in the next" # average lifespan is 18 years: https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=American_black_bear&oldid=1227551752 # another article (https://myfwc.com/wildlifehabitats/wildlife/bear/facts/life-expectancy/#:~:text=Two%20of%20the%20biggest%20threats,of%20a%20new%20home%20range.) says that adulthood is about 4 years # adult for 14 of those years say, then let’s assume an exponential mortality curve, so the exponent is -1/14 and then that means that the adult stasis value should be exp(-1/14) \approx 0.9310627797. with ui.tooltip(id="f3_tooltip", placement="right"): ui.input_slider( "f3", "Fertility (f3)", min=0, max=1, value=0.20, step=0.01, # post="%" # pre="." ) ui.HTML("""
""") "The average number of cubs that are produced in a given year per living adult bear" # fertility seems somewhat variable # the poster cited below predicts that the bear population in utah is stable, so I'll choose a value that reflects this based on the other parameters # 0.20 seems to be a good number based on the slider to reflect the poster's predicted growth rate of 0.97 # ====================INTRO==================== ui.markdown(""" A population is a group of organisms, like people or bears, that live in the same area and interbreed. Population dynamics is the study of how a population changes over time, including the numbers and ages of the organisms in the population. The purpose of this app is to highlight connections between linear algebra and population dynamics. __Eigenvalues and eigenvectors__ are important concepts from linear algebra that can be used to model population dynamics using __transition matrices__. """) # ====================MATH INTRO==================== # ui.markdown( # """ # Let the values in the __state vector__ $$\mathbf{v_i} = [a_i, b_i, c_i, ...]^T$$ represent states in some system at time i. For example, let each entry represent the number of bears of different ages. # A transition matrix *A* is a square matrix such that the transition matrix, when right multiplied by a state vector representing the state at time i, yields another state vector at time i+1. In other words, $$A\mathbf{v_i} = \mathbf{v_{i+1}}.$$ # The **principal eigenvalue** of the transition matrix, shown below on the left side of the inequality, is the eigenvalue with the largest absolute value. The **principal eigenvector** is the eigenvector associated with this eigenvalue. # $$A\mathbf{v_i} = \lambda_i\mathbf{v_i}$$ # $$|\lambda_1| \geq |\lambda_2| \geq |\lambda_3| ...$$ # """ # ) # ui.markdown( # """ # Explanation of relevant linear algebra... # - Define and help students understand eigenvectors and values # - Transition matrix operation # - Define principal eigenvector # - Touch on significance of Perron-Frobenius theorem # - Explain why the principal eigenvector wins out # - Explain on the population size graph""") # ====================MODEL EXPLANATION==================== with ui.layout_columns(fill=False): with ui.value_box(): "State diagram" # @render.express # def num(): # "This: " + str(100 - input.m1()) @render.plot def diagplot(): from pathlib import Path dir = Path(__file__).resolve().parent img = np.asarray(Image.open(str(dir / "diag3.png"))) # print(img) # print(img.shape) # draw image myplot = plt.imshow(img) # specify axes ax = plt.gca() # add text # fontsize fs = 9 # # row 1: fertility r1y = 175 ax.text(1060, r1y, priper(int(100*input.f3())), fontsize=fs, weight='bold') # # row 2: stases r2y = 460 ax.text(850-15, r2y, priper(input.s2()), fontsize=fs, weight='bold', color = font()) ax.text(1600-15, r2y, priper(input.s3()), fontsize=fs, weight='bold') # # row 3: maturations r3y = 702 ax.text(655, r3y, priper(input.m1()), fontsize=fs, weight='bold') ax.text(1405, r3y, priper(input.m2()), fontsize=fs, weight='bold', color = font()) r4y = 985 # row 4: calculate and add deaths # handle negative percentage strings ax.text(450-50, r4y, priper(100-input.m1()), fontsize=fs, weight='bold') ax.text(1250-50, r4y, priper(100-input.s2()-input.m2()), fontsize=fs, weight='bold', color = font()) ax.text(1950-50, r4y, priper(100-input.s3()), fontsize=fs, weight='bold') ax.axis('off') return myplot @render.express def texthighlight(): message = "The numbers on the arrows leaving each age class, excluding fertility, should be nonnegative and should sum to one." if not check_valid(): message = """""" + message + """""" ui.markdown( """This diagram represents our assumptions about how the bear population grows and changes in the span of one year. The values represent the proportion of bears in each state (age class) that we assume will transition to each other respective state. You can adjust the values by moving the sliders in the sidebar on the left.""" ) # ui.markdown( # """ # - This diagram displays the assumptions about the bears that allow the population to be modeled with a [matrix population model](https://kevintshoemaker.github.io/NRES-470/LAB4.html). Each arrow represents events that could happen to a bear of a given age class from year to year. For example, a cub can only either die or mature into a juvenile bear in the passing of a year, while a juvenile may die, remain a juvenile, mature into an adult. # - """ + message + """ This is because these arrows represent bears moving between classes. The numbers represent the probabilities that a bear in the given age class will transition to the class indicated by the arrow. Since the numbers are probabilities, they must be between zero and one, inclusive. We assume that every living bear will follow exactly one of the arrows each year. So the probabilities of each arrow being chosen must sum to one. # - We assume that each bear in that age class must either die, stay in the same age class (stasis, does not occur with cubs), or transition to the next age class (maturation, does not occur with adults). Fertility represents the reproduction of adult bears, which does not require the adults to leave their age class, so it is not included in the sum. # - Although our model really has four states - cub, juvenile, adult, and dead - we can model the dead state implicitly since it is an 'absorbing' state (no dead bear can become a living cub, juvenile, or adult). Beacuse of this, you will see that we don't give death a row or column in the transition matrix. The probability of death can be inferred by the other parameters as shown in the state diagram. # """ # ) # ====================MATH EXPLANATION==================== with ui.layout_columns(fill=False): with ui.value_box(): "Transition matrix" # @render.express # def value(): # input.alpha_val() # xmin = 500 # xmax = 625 # ymin = 200 # ymax = 675 # dx = 170 # bigx = 200 # with ui.tooltip(id="tmatrix_tooltip", delay="""{ "show": 0, "hide": 3000}"""): @render.plot def mplimgplot(): from pathlib import Path dir = Path(__file__).resolve().parent img = np.asarray(Image.open(str(dir / "modified_mymatrix.png"))) # print(img) # print(img.shape) # -----------------draw image----------------- myplot = plt.imshow(img) # specify axes ax = plt.gca() # -----------------plot values in left matrix----------------- # values for easy adjustment dx = 512+13 dy = 280 w = 175 h = w # # for mymatrix.png: # dx = 100 # dy = 125 # w = 175 # h = w # row 1 ax.text(0*w+dx, 0*h+dy, '$s_1$') ax.text(1*w+dx, 0*h+dy, '$f_2$') ax.text(2*w+dx, 0*h+dy, '$f_3$') # row 2 ax.text(0*w+dx, 1*h+dy, '$m_1$') ax.text(1*w+dx, 1*h+dy, '$s_2$') ax.text(2*w+dx, 1*h+dy, '0') # row 3 ax.text(0*w+dx, 2*h+dy, '0') ax.text(1*w+dx, 2*h+dy, '$m_2$') ax.text(2*w+dx, 2*h+dy, '$s_3$') # -----------------plot numbers in right matrix----------------- # values for easy adjustment dx = 1230 dy = 280 # w = 175 # h = w # row 1 ax.text(0*w+dx, 0*h+dy, '0') ax.text(1*w+dx, 0*h+dy, '0') ax.text(2*w+dx, 0*h+dy, priper(int(100*input.f3()))) # row 2 ax.text(0*w+dx, 1*h+dy, priper(input.m1())) ax.text(1*w+dx, 1*h+dy, priper(input.s2())) ax.text(2*w+dx, 1*h+dy, '0') # row 3 ax.text(0*w+dx, 2*h+dy, '0') ax.text(1*w+dx, 2*h+dy, priper(input.m2())) ax.text(2*w+dx, 2*h+dy, priper(input.s3())) # bonus with switches params = (500, 625, 200, 675, 170, 200) # -----------------rows----------------- if(input.showrow()): ax.add_collection(row_collection(*params)) # -----------------columns----------------- if(input.showcol()): ax.add_collection(col_collection(*params)) # -----------------line boundaries----------------- if(input.showdiag()): ax.add_collection(diag_collection(*params)) # final adjustments # remove axes ax.axis('off') return myplot ui.input_switch("showcol", "Show age class (pre-transition)", value=False) ui.input_switch("showrow", "Show age class (post-transition)", value=False) ui.input_switch("showdiag", "Show parameter groups (stasis, maturation, and fertility)", value=False) # ui.markdown( # """ # Our [**transition matrix**](https://kevintshoemaker.github.io/NRES-470/LAB4.html) has all non-negative real values. By the [Perron-Frobenius theorem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perron%E2%80%93Frobenius_theorem), this implies that, the principal eigenvalue and each entry in the principal eigenvector will also be non-negative real numbers. # - Stasis (s) values represent what fraction of bears in a given age category will remain in that age category the next year. The parameter s1 is always zero here, because all cubs that live through their first year are considered yearlings, a type of juvenile bear. Stasis values are placed on the main diagonal. # - Maturation (m) values represent what fraction of bears in a given age category that will mature to the next age category in the next year. There is no m3 here, becuase adult bear is the last age category we are considering. # - Fertility (f) value for a given age category is the average number of new bears born to an individual in that age category each year. The parameter f2 is always zero here because we assume that juvenile bears cannot reproduce until they become adults. # - The subscript on each value indicates which age category it is referring to (cub, juvenile, or adult). # """ # ) ui.markdown( """ The transition matrix summarizes the information contained in the state diagram above, some of it explicitly and some implicitly. It allows us to use linear algebra to quickly calculate how the bear population should change over time given the assumptions we made in the state diagram. The switches above help explain the connection between the transition matrix and the state diagram.""" ) # ====================VISUALIZE==================== with ui.layout_columns(fill=False): with ui.value_box(): ui.markdown( """ Population distribution """ ) # long term predicted population dist. @render.express def peigvec(): eigvec = np.round(pevec()/np.sum(pevec()), decimals=2) streigvec = str(list(eigvec)) ui.markdown( "**v**_1 = " + streigvec + "^T") @render.plot def pie(): labels = ["Cubs", "Juveniles", "Adults"] cols = ['#1f77b4', '#ff7f0e', '#2ca02c'] total = pevec() ax = plt.gca() # plt.title("Long term population distribution") plt.title("Utah Black Bear Demographics") ax.axis("equal") # Fill in a pie chart with images. adopted from # https://stackoverflow.com/questions/44528024/insert-image-into-pie-chart-slice # total = [5,7,4] # plt.title('Bears') # plt.gca().axis("equal") # plot a colored pie chart in the background ax.pie(total, startangle=90, colors=cols) wedges, texts = ax.pie(total, startangle=90, labels=labels, wedgeprops = { 'linewidth': 1, "edgecolor" :"k","fill":False, }) # find the bisecting vector of each pie wedge as an angle from (1, 0) in radians centroids = np.pi/2 + 2 * np.pi * np.array([(sum(total[:i]) + total[i]/2)/sum(total) for i, tot in enumerate(total)]) # get the x, y for these vectors (but only half of the length so that the images end up within the slices) # rows are the three images and columns are x vs y positions = np.stack([np.cos(centroids), np.sin(centroids)]).T/2 # adjust image zoom zooms = [0.4,0.4,0.4] for i in range(3): # get the filename for the respective image filename = "{}.jpg".format(labels[i]) # read in image files im = None if filename=="Adults.jpg": im = imadults() elif filename=="Cubs.jpg": im = imcubs() elif filename=="Juveniles.jpg": im = imjuveniles() # get the path? to the respective wedge of the pie chart and begin plotting there path = wedges[i].get_path() patch = PathPatch(path, facecolor='none') ax.add_patch(patch) # place image at the respective locations and clip using the wedge (?) imagebox = OffsetImage(im, zoom=zooms[i], clip_path=patch, zorder=-10) ab = AnnotationBbox(imagebox, positions[i], xycoords='data', pad=0, frameon=False) ax.add_artist(ab) # overlay the clip so that for sure the images get clipped into the wedges wedges[i].set_zorder(10) # ui.markdown( # """ # The **principal eigenvector** of the transition matrix represents the age distribution the population will approach over time. The age distribution of the population should naturally approach this ratio as time goes on. # """ # ) ui.markdown( """Though some bear populations might start out with different cub-juvinile-adult ratios, the state diagram predicts that the age distribution of any bear population will eventually approach a stable ratio. The principal eigenvector of the transition matrix, shown above, represents the age distribution the bear population is expected to approach.""" ) with ui.value_box(): ui.markdown( """ Population growth """ ) # long term predicted population growth @render.express def peigval(): "λ_1 = " + str(np.round(peval(), decimals=2)) @render.plot def pred(): x, y = prediction() # convert x value to current years from datetime import date year_ = int(date.today().year) plt.plot((x+year_).astype(int), y.astype(int), 'ko-') plt.ylim(bottom=0, top=max(3000, y[4])) plt.ylabel("Predicted population size") plt.xlabel("year") plt.title("Utah Black Bear Count") ax = plt.gca() # ax.title("Long term population growth") ui.markdown( """As the bear population approaches the age distribution shown to the left, the state diagram predicts a characteristic population growth rate, determined by the principal eigenvalue. Use the sliders to see how changing the parameters in the model changes the eventual growth rate and age distribution of the bear population predicted by our state diagram.""" ) # ui.markdown( # """ # The **principal eigenvalue** of the transition matrix represents the maximum growth rate of the population. When the age breakdown doesn't match the principal eigenvector, the overall growth rate may be inconsistent, or lower than the predicted rate. # """ # ) # with ui.layout_columns(fill=False): # with ui.value_box(): # render an image standalone # @render.image # def image(): # from pathlib import Path # dir = Path(__file__).resolve().parent # img = {"src": str(dir / "mymath.png"), "width": "100%"} # return img # having trouble centering, so I'm just using matplotlib # @render.plot # def mplimgplot2(): # from pathlib import Path # dir = Path(__file__).resolve().parent # img = np.asarray(Image.open(str(dir / "mymath.png"))) # # print(img) # # print(img.shape) # # draw image # myplot = plt.imshow(img) # ax = plt.gca() # ax.axis('off') # return myplot ui.markdown( """ Inspired by work from Brenden Orocu, Dr. Mark Belk, and others, on modeling black bear populations in eastern Utah: https://byu.app.box.com/s/typ96vcpp010vyytqkufpd1qptcnldh3 Images and demographic information for the default parameter estimates came from the following sources: “American Black Bear.” 2024. In Wikipedia. https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=American_black_bear&oldid=1227551752. Animals are Awesome, dir. 2017. Baby Black Bear Cubs Playing Compilation. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-2cj5pPe778. “Black Bear | Size, Weight, Habitat, Diet, & Facts | Britannica.” n.d. Accessed June 10, 2024. https://www.britannica.com/animal/black-bear. “Facts about Florida Black Bears: Life Expectancy.” n.d.-a. Florida Fish And Wildlife Conservation Commission. Accessed June 10, 2024. https://myfwc.com/wildlifehabitats/wildlife/bear/facts/life-expectancy/. “———.” n.d.-b. Florida Fish And Wildlife Conservation Commission. Accessed June 10, 2024. https://myfwc.com/wildlifehabitats/wildlife/bear/facts/life-expectancy/. KUTV, Sara Knox. 2021. “Utah’s Drought May Lead to More Aggressive Black Bears.” KUTV. May 18, 2021. https://kutv.com/news/local/utahs-drought-may-lead-to-more-aggressive-black-bears. Schnee (KUTV), Brian. 2024. “Biologists Checking on Utah’s Healthy Bear Population, Visiting Dens across the State.” KUTV. March 19, 2024. https://kutv.com/news/local/utah-biologists-checking-on-bear-dens-across-the-state-dwr-wildlife. """ ) # # render an image standalone # @render.image # def image(): # from pathlib import Path # dir = Path(__file__).resolve().parent # img = {"src": str(dir / "mymatrix.png"), "width": "100px"} # return img # -------------------------------------------------------- # Reactive calculations and effects # -------------------------------------------------------- # linear algebra @reactive.calc def transition_matrix(): return np.array([ [0, 0, 100*input.f3()], [input.m1(), input.s2(), 0], [0, input.m2(), input.s3()] ])/100 @reactive.calc def eigs(): return np.linalg.eig(transition_matrix()) @reactive.calc def prineigs(): # print(eigs()) evals = eigs()[0] evecs = eigs()[1] i = np.argmax(evals) return (np.abs(evals[i]), np.abs(evecs[:,i])) @reactive.calc def peval(): return prineigs()[0] @reactive.calc def pevec(): return prineigs()[1] # plotting population @reactive.calc def prediction(init_pop = 2000): # about 2000 black bears in Utah in 2024: # https://kutv.com/news/local/utah-biologists-checking-on-bear-dens-across-the-state-dwr-wildlife years = 5 x = np.array(range(years)) # make array full of peval() entries to raise to the power later pevalarr = peval()+np.zeros(years) return (x, init_pop*np.power(pevalarr, x)) # # helperfunctions # @reactive.calc # def myimg(filename): # if filename=="Adults.jpg": # return imadults() # elif filename=="Cubs.jpg": # return imcubs() # elif filename=="Juveniles.jpg": # return imjuveniles() @reactive.calc def imadults(): from pathlib import Path dir = Path(__file__).resolve().parent return np.asarray(Image.open(str(dir / "Adults.jpg"))) @reactive.calc def imcubs(): from pathlib import Path dir = Path(__file__).resolve().parent return np.asarray(Image.open(str(dir / "Cubs.jpg"))) @reactive.calc def imjuveniles(): from pathlib import Path dir = Path(__file__).resolve().parent return np.asarray(Image.open(str(dir / "Juveniles.jpg"))) # help plotting percentages def priper(num): if abs(num) >= 100: return(str(num/100)) else: ret = '.' if abs(num) < 10: ret += '0' if num < 0: ret = '-' + ret return ret + str(abs(num)) @reactive.calc def check_valid(): # make sure we are not assuming that we can pull from over 100% of the juveniles if (100 - input.s2() - input.m2() >= 0): return True return False @reactive.calc def font(): # make the font red if there is an error if check_valid(): return 'k' else: return 'r' # ab = AnnotationBbox(imagebox, xy, xycoords='data', pad=0, frameon=False) # subax.add_artist(ab)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib.patches import PathPatch
from matplotlib.offsetbox import OffsetImage, AnnotationBbox
import numpy as np
from PIL import Image

from matplotlib.collections import PatchCollection
from matplotlib.patches import Polygon


def col_collection(xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax, dx, bigx):
    """Color the columns on the transition matrix
    
    Returns a PatchCollection appropriately sized and colored for the matrix image"""
    colors = ['#1f77b4', '#ff7f0e', '#2ca02c']

    arr1 = np.array([
        [xmin, ymin],
        [xmin, ymax],
        [xmax, ymax],
        [xmax, ymin],
    ])

    temparr = arr1

    mypatches = list()
    for three in range(2):
        for pat in range(3):
            print(colors[pat])
            mypatches.append(Polygon(temparr, closed=True))
            temparr[:,0] += dx
        temparr[:,0] += bigx

    coll = PatchCollection(mypatches, alpha=0.4)
    coll.set(facecolor=2*colors)
    return coll
        
def row_collection(xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax, dx, bigx):
    """Color the rows on the transition matrix
    
    Returns a PatchCollection appropriately sized and colored for the matrix image"""
    colors = ['#1f77b4', '#ff7f0e', '#2ca02c']
    rowthick = (ymax-ymin)/4
    rowskip = (ymax-ymin-rowthick)/2
    rowarr = np.array([
        [xmin, ymin],
        [xmax+2*dx, ymin],
        [xmax+2*dx, ymin+rowthick],
        [xmin, ymin+rowthick]
    ])

    temparr = rowarr.copy()
    mypatchesr = list()
    for three in range(2):
        for pat in range(3):
            print(colors[pat])
            mypatchesr.append(Polygon(temparr, closed=True))
            temparr[:,1] += int(rowskip)
        temparr = rowarr.copy()
        temparr[:,0] += 3*dx + bigx


    collr = PatchCollection(mypatchesr, alpha=0.4)
    collr.set(facecolor=2*colors)
    
    return collr

def diag_collection(xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax, dx, bigx):
    """Outline the groups of variables on the transition matrix
    
    Returns a PatchCollection appropriately sized for the matrix image"""
    stretch = 2/4
    pull = 5/8
    # drawing diag
    rowthick = (ymax-ymin)/4
    rowskip = (ymax-ymin-rowthick)/2
    gap = (stretch)*(xmax-xmin)

    x1 = xmin
    x2 = xmin + gap
    x3 = xmax + 2*dx
    x4 = x3
    x5 = xmax + 2*dx - pull*rowthick*(x3-x2)/((ymax - gap)-ymin)
    x6 = x1

    y1 = ymin
    y2 = y1
    y3 = ymax - gap
    y4 = ymax
    y5 = ymax
    y6 = ymin + pull*rowthick

    diarr = np.array([
        [x1, y1],
        [x2, y2],
        [x3, y3],
        [x4, y4],
        [x5, y5],
        [x6, y6],
    ])

    # drawing upper row minus diag
    x7 = xmin + (3/4)*(xmax-xmin)
    x8 = x3
    x9 = x3
    x10 = x7 + rowthick*(x3-x2)/(y3-y2)

    y7 = y2
    y8 = y2
    y9 = y2+rowthick
    y10 = y2+rowthick

    upparr = np.array([
        [x7, y7],
        [x8, y8],
        [x9, y9],
        [x10, y10], 
    ])

    # drawing lower diag
    y11 = ymin + rowthick - 10
    y12 = ymax
    y13 = ymax
    y14 = ymin + rowskip + pull*rowthick

    x11 = x1
    x12 = x1+(y12-y11)*(x3-x2)/(y3-y2)
    x13 = x1+(y13-y14)*(x3-x2)/(y3-y2)
    x14 = x1

    lowarr = np.array([
        [x11, y11],
        [x12, y12],
        [x13, y13],
        [x14, y14], 
    ])

    # now add them all to the patch
    arrlist = [diarr, upparr, lowarr]
    borders = list()
    for three in range(2):
        for arr in arrlist:
            num = 0
            if three == 1:
                num = 3*dx + bigx
            arr[:,0] += num
            borders.append(Polygon(arr, closed=True))

    coll2 = PatchCollection(borders)
    coll2.set(facecolor=(1,1,1,0), edgecolor=(0,0,0,1))

    return coll2
